<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910322-0188</DOCNO><DOCID>910322-0188.</DOCID><HL>   International:   British Aerospace to Cut   Additional 4,700 Workers   ----   Special to The Wall Street Journal</HL><DATE>03/22/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A6</SO><CO>   U.BA</CO><IN>AEROSPACE (ARO)</IN><LP>   LONDON -- British Aerospace PLC, the U.K.'s largestmanufacturing group, said it will slash an additional 4,700employees from its work force.   The group said its commercial aircraft operations willreduce staff to 24,000 from 26,500. Also, its Dynamics Ltd.subsidiary will cut staff to 6,900 from 9,100.</LP><TEXT>   In 1990, the commercial aircraft division posted a 133%increase in trading profit to #35 million ($62.5 million), ona 14% rise in sales to #1.58 billion. Nevertheless, BritishAerospace said the cuts reflected a need to improve groupcompetitiveness and reduce costs.   In November, British Aerospace announced the closure oftwo plants in its military aircraft division, cutting staffover 2 1/2 years by 5,000, to 22,000. The staff reductionsfollow operational reviews carried out during the past year.   The staff layoffs in the aerospace division were promptedby world recession, price pressures on air fares and thecontinuing weak dollar, which impacts the group's results,the managing director of the commercial aircraft divisionsaid.   Aerospace division chairman Sydney Gillibrand said, &quot;it isimperative that we achieve further improvements in operatingefficiency if we are to maintain a competitive position inthe world.&quot;</TEXT></DOC>